The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 BRIEFS

 Calcutta, March 28: The North Bengal State Transport Corporation will pay Rs 4.5 lakh in damages to Abdul Malek, who lost his right arm after a bus hit him in 1992. 

 Then four years old, he was knocked down at Raiganj in North Dinajpur, 400 km from here. A tribunal had in 1999 asked the corporation to pay Rs 87,500 to Abdul, now writing his HS exam with his left hand. He got nothing. After his father moved the high court, the corporation agreed to pay the damages, now amounting Rs 4.5 lakh. 

 Calcutta: The high court on Tuesday granted bail to a lifer whose appeal against the trial court order could not be heard in 11 years. The police could not apparently get the papers ready. Chinu Seikh of Birbhum was convicted of murder. 

 Calcutta: United Air-lines, which has an office in Salt Lake, is planning to expand its software development centre. Its vice-president and chief development officer met the chief minister.

 College unrest: Stud- ents of a Salt Lake tech school held the principal and some of their teachers hostage till late night. They were demanding 100 per cent placement.




